A '''porters' lodge''' (colloquially, '''plodge''')<ref name="Varsity2014">{{cite news |last=O’Neill |first=Anne |url=http://www.varsity.co.uk/lifestyle/7414 |title=A Cambridge Dictionary |work=Varsity |location=Cambridge |publisher=Varsity Publications Ltd. |date=2014-08-25 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140907154104/http://www.varsity.co.uk/lifestyle/7414 |archivedate=2014-09-07 |accessdate=2014-10-01 }}</ref> is a place near the entrance of a building where one or more [[Porter (college)|porters]] can be found to respond to enquiries from the public and direct them around the building. It is particularly associated with [[university]] accommodation in the [[United Kingdom]], [[United States]] and [[Canada]] (such as the majority of colleges of the Universities of [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], [[University of Durham|Durham]], [[University of York|York]] and [[University of Toronto|Toronto]]).<ref>[http://www.kings.cam.ac.uk/facilities/porters/ King's College porters' lodge] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704080909/http://www.kings.cam.ac.uk/facilities/porters/ |date=4 July 2009 }}, [[King's College, Cambridge]].</ref><ref>[http://www.kings.cam.ac.uk/visitors/tours/grounds/porterslodge.html Tour of the grounds: Porters' Lodge] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614012213/http://www.kings.cam.ac.uk/visitors/tours/grounds/porterslodge.html |date=14 June 2008 }}, King's College, Cambridge.</ref>
[[Oxbridge]] porters' lodges typically also house the [[Pigeon-hole messagebox|pigeon-holes]] for students' and [[Fellow]]s' mail.<ref name="Varsity2014"/>
