{{Infobox language family |name=Siouan |altname=Siouan–Catawban |region=central [[North America]] |familycolor=American |family=One of the world's primary [[language family|language families]] |child1=[[Catawban languages|Catawban]] (Eastern) † |child2=[[Western Siouan languages|Siouan proper]] (Western) |map=Siouan-Catawban langs.png |mapcaption=Pre-contact distribution of the Siouan–Catawban languages |iso2=sio |glotto=siou1252 |lingua=64-A |glottorefname=Siouan }}
'''Siouan''' or '''Siouan–Catawban''' is a [[language family]] of [[North America]] that is located primarily in the [[Great Plains]], [[Ohio]] and [[Mississippi]] valleys and southeastern North America with a few other languages in the east.
==Name== Authors who call the entire family ''Siouan'' distinguish the two branches as ''[[Western Siouan languages|Western Siouan]]'' and ''[[Eastern Siouan languages|Eastern Siouan]]'' or as ''Siouan-proper'' and ''Catawban''. Others restrict the name "Siouan" to the western branch and use the name ''Siouan–Catawban'' for the entire family. Generally, however, the name "Siouan" is used without distinction.
==Family division==
Siouan languages can be grouped into the [[Western Siouan languages]] and [[Catawban languages]]. The Western Siouan languages can be divided into Missouri River languages (such as [[Crow language|Crow]] and [[Hidatsa language|Hidatsa]]), [[Mandan language|Mandan]], Mississippi River languages (such as [[Sioux language|Dakotan]], [[Chiwere language|Chiwere]]-[[Winnebago language|Winnebago]], and [[Dhegihan languages|Dhegihan]] languages), and [[Ohio Valley Siouan languages|Ohio Valley Siouan]] branches. The Catawban languages consist only of [[Catawba language|Catawban]] and [[Woccon language|Woccon]].
==Proto-Siouan==
===Previous proposals=== There is a certain amount of [[comparative method|comparative work]] in Siouan–Catawban languages. Wolff (1950–51) is among the first and more complete works on the subject. Wolff reconstructed the system of proto-Siouan, and this was modified by Matthews (1958). The latter's system is shown below: {| class="wikitable" ! ![[labial consonant|Labial]] ![[alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[palatal consonant|Palatal]] ![[velar consonant|Velar]] ![[glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- ! [[plosive]] | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*p}} | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*t}} | | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*k}} | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*ʔ}} |- ! [[fricative]] | | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*s}} | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*ʃ}} | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*x}} | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*h}} |- ! [[nasal stop|nasal]] | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*m}} | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*n}} | | | |- ! [[approximant]] | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*w}} | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*r}} | style="text-align:center; font-size:larger;" |{{IPA|*j}} | | |} With respect to vowels, five oral vowels are being reconstructed {{IPA|/*i, *e, *a, *o, *u/}} and three [[nasal vowel]]s {{IPA|/*ĩ, *ã, *ũ/}}. Wolff also reconstructed some consonantal clusters {{IPA|/*tk, *kʃ, *ʃk, *sp/}}.
===Current proposal=== Collaborative work involving a number of Siouanists started at the 1984 Comparative Siouan Workshop at the University of Colorado with the goal of creating a comparative Siouan dictionary that would include Proto-Siouan reconstructions.<ref>Rankin, Robert L., Carter, Richard T., Jones, A. Wesley, Koontz, John E., Rood, David S. & Hartmann, Iren (Eds.). (2015). ''Comparative Siouan Dictionary''. Leipzig, Germany: Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology. (Available online at http://csd.clld.org, Accessed on 2015-12-13.)</ref> This work yielded a different analysis of the phonemic system of Proto-Siouan, which appears below:<ref>Rankin, Robert L., Carter, Richard T. & Jones, A. Wesley (n.d.). ''Proto-Siouan Phonology and Grammar''. Ms. University of Kansas.</ref>
====Consonants==== {| class="wikitable" ! colspan="2" | ! style="text-align: center;" | [[labial consonant|Labial]] ! style="text-align: center;" | [[coronal consonant|Coronal]] ! style="text-align: center;" | [[palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! style="text-align: center;" | [[velar consonant|Velar]] ! style="text-align: center;" | [[glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- | rowspan="4" style="text-align: center;" | [[plosive consonant|'''Plosive''']] | style="text-align: center;" | [[tenuis consonant|<small>'''plain'''</small>]] | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*p}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*t}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*k}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*ʔ}} |- | style="text-align: center;" | [[ejective consonant|<small>'''glottalized'''</small>]] | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*pʼ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*tʼ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*kʼ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | |- | style="text-align: center;" | [[preaspiration|<small>'''preaspriated'''</small>]] | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*ʰp}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*ʰt}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*ʰk}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | |- | style="text-align: center;" | [[aspirated consonant|<small>'''postaspirated'''</small>]] | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*pʰ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*tʰ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*kʰ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | |- | rowspan="2" style="text-align: center;" | [[fricative consonant|'''Fricative''']] | style="text-align: center;" | [[tenuis consonant|<small>'''plain'''</small>]] | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*s}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*ʃ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*x}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*h}} |- | style="text-align: center;" | [[ejective consonant|<small>'''glottalized'''</small>]] | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*sʼ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*ʃʼ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*xʼ}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | |- | colspan="2" style="text-align: center;" | '''[[Sonorant]]''' | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*w}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*r}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | {{IPA|*j}} | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | |- | colspan="2" style="text-align: center;" | '''[[Obstruent]]''' | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | *W | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | *R | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | | style="text-align: center; font-size:larger;" | |}
In Siouanist literature (e.g., Rankin et al. 2015), [[Americanist phonetic notation#Consonants|Americanist phonetic]] transcriptions are the norm, so IPA *{{IPA|ʃ}} is Americanist *š, IPA *j is Americanist *y, and so on.
The major change to the previously-proposed system by systematically accounting for the distribution of multiple stop series in modern Siouan languages by tracing them back to multiple stop series in the proto-language. Previous analysis posited only a single stop series.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wolff | first1 = Hans | year = 1950 | title = Comparative Siouan II. | url = | journal = International Journal of American Linguistics | volume = 16 | issue = 3| pages = 113–121 | doi=10.1086/464075}}</ref>
Many of the consonant clusters proposed by Wolf (1950{{endash}}1951) can be accounted for due to [[syncope (phonology)|syncopation]] of short vowels before stressed syllables. For example, Matthews (1958: 129) gives *wróke as the proto-form for 'male.' With added data from a larger set of Siouan languages since the middle of the twentieth century, Rankin et al. (2015) give *waroː(-ka) as the reconstructed form for 'male.'
Unlike Wolff and Matthew's proposals, there are no posited nasal consonants in Proto-Siouan. Nasal consonants only arise in daughter languages when followed by a nasal vowel.<ref>Some Siouan languages have however developed a phonemic contrast between the non-nasal sonorants w- and r- and the corresponding nasals m- and n-. These historical developments are presented in the following article: {{cite journal |last1=Michaud|first1=Alexis | authorlink1 =Alexis Michaud|last2=Jacques |first2=Guillaume |last3=Rankin|first3=Robert L.|year=2012 |title=Historical Transfer of Nasality Between Consonantal Onset and Vowel: From C to V or from V to C? |journal=Diachronica |volume=29 |issue=2 |pages=201–230 |publisher= |doi= 10.1075/dia.29.2.04mic|url=http://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00580260/en/ }} </ref> In addition, there is a set of sounds that represent obstruentized versions of their corresponding sonorants. These sounds have different reflexes in daughter languages, with *w appearing as [w] or [m] in most daughter languages, while *W has a reflex of [w], [b], [mb], or [p]. The actual phonetic value of these obstruents is an issue of some debate, with some arguing that they arise through geminated *w+*w or *r+*r sequences or a laryngeal plus *w or *r.<ref>Rankin, Robert L., Carter, Richard T. & Jones, A. Wesley. (n.d.). ''Proto-Siouan Phonology and Grammar''. Ms. University of Kansas.</ref>
====Vowels==== Previous work on Proto-Siouan only posited single vowel length. However, phonemic vowel length exists in several Siouan languages such as [[hidatsa language|Hidatsa]], [[winnebago language|Ho-Chunk]], and [[tutelo language|Tutelo]]. Rankin et al. (2015) analyze numerous instances of long vowels as present due to common inheritance rather than common innovation. The five oral vowels and three nasal vowels posited by earlier scholars is expanded to include a distinction between short and long vowels. The proposed Proto-Siouan vowel system appears below:
